# Rebuild for in-app update panel (explicit user request only)

**Scope:** This guidance applies **only** when the user clearly asks for this workflow. Typical phrases: “rebuild for the update panel”, “run xcodebuild so I get the sidebar update”, “refresh the running app with a build”, “build so I can relaunch from Jot”.

**Default:** After normal code edits, **do not** run `xcodebuild` unless the user requested a build, asked you to verify compilation, asked for tests, or used one of the phrases above. Routine implementation work does **not** imply an automatic rebuild.

When the user **did** request this, run a Debug build from the repository root (trimmed log tail keeps output short):

```bash
cd /Users/mohebanwari/development/Jot && xcodebuild -project Jot.xcodeproj -scheme Jot -configuration Debug build -allowProvisioningUpdates 2>&1 | tail -8
```

**Why:** Jot’s `BuildWatcherManager` (DEBUG only) watches `Jot.debug.dylib`. When the binary updates while the app is running, an **update panel can appear at the bottom of the left sidebar** (above Trash/Settings). The user relaunches from there.

**After the build:** Follow `feedback_no_relaunch_after_build.mdc` — no killing the app, no `open`, no `touch` on the bundle. Confirm `BUILD SUCCEEDED`, tell the user the build is ready, and that they can use the update panel when they want.
